        introduction: "The Principality of Andorra, a small 468 km² Pyrenean state wedged between France and Spain, attracts over 8 million visitors annually, mainly for duty-free shopping and ski resorts. Andorra la Vella, Europe's highest capital (1,023 m altitude), offers an unmatched concentration of duty-free shops: perfumes, electronics, spirits and tobacco at unbeatable prices. In winter, the Grandvalira (the Pyrenees' largest ski area, 210 km of runs) and Vallnord resorts attract skiers from across southern France. The journey from Toulouse crosses spectacular Ariège landscapes: the Niaux caves (Magdalenian cave art), Montségur castle (the last Cathar refuge), Ax-les-Thermes spa town, then the climb to Pas de la Case (2,085 m), the highest border crossing in the French Pyrenees. A taxi is particularly suited for this mountain journey: winding roads in winter with ice risks, mountain passes, and returns often laden with heavy duty-free purchases that would not fit on a bus.",
        itineraire: "From Toulouse, your driver takes the A66 motorway towards Foix. The A66 crosses Toulouse's southern suburbs (Portet-sur-Garonne, Vernet) then follows the Ariège river. The motorway ends at Pamiers and the road becomes the N20, a national road running up the entire Ariège valley. You pass Foix, recognisable by its three-towered castle perched on a rocky peak, then Tarascon-sur-Ariège (access to Niaux and Bédeilhac caves). After Luzenac and its talc quarry (Europe's largest), you reach Ax-les-Thermes, a spa town at 720 m altitude, the last comfortable stop before the ascent. The N20 then climbs in tight switchbacks towards Pas de la Case, with 8-10% gradients and tunnel sections. At Pas de la Case (2,085 m), you cross the Andorran border. The descent to Andorra la Vella (37 km) passes through Soldeu, El Tarter and Encamp. Tolls only apply to the A66 (about €6); the N20 and Andorra are toll-free. Allow 2h30 in summer, 3h in winter (snow tyres or chains mandatory November to March).",
        conseils: "In winter (November to March), the journey to Andorra requires winter tyres or chains. Our vehicles are systematically fitted with winter tyres from November to April. Pas de la Case can be closed by snow (check road conditions at inforoute-ariege.fr). Alternative: the Envalira tunnel (€4 toll) bypasses the pass when closed. For duty-free shopping, the best deals are on Avenue Meritxell in Andorra la Vella: perfumes (20-30% cheaper than France), electronics (10-20% cheaper), spirits and tobacco (50-70% cheaper). Mind customs allowances on return: 300 cigarettes, 1.5L spirits, 5L wine, 75L beer per person. For skiing at Grandvalira, day passes cost €45-55. If combining shopping and skiing, plan at least 2 days. The loaded return journey is the best argument for a taxi: no limited space as on a bus.",
        comparaisonTransport: "The Andbus service connects Toulouse to Andorra la Vella in 3h30 for €32-40. It is economical but inflexible (2-3 departures daily) with no space for bulky purchases. No train reaches Andorra (the nearest station is L'Hospitalet in France, 20 km from Pas de la Case, with no reliable shuttle). By personal car, expect €25 in fuel and €6 in tolls, but the mountain road is stressful in winter and the loaded return is tiring. The TaxiNeo taxi at €280 — €350 is the premium solution: experienced mountain driver, winter-equipped vehicle, large boot for purchases. For 4 passengers, the cost (€70-88 per person) is reasonable for a VIP service including bag carrying.",
